JavaScript Object Management:

- Property Management Methods:
    // Adding or changing an object property
    Object.defineProperty(object, property, descriptor)

    // Adding or changing object properties
    Object.defineProperties(object, descriptors)

    // Accessing a Property
    Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(object, property)

    // Accessing Properties
    Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptors(object)

    // Returns all properties as an array
    Object.getOwnPropertyNames(object)

    // Accessing the prototype
    Object.getPrototypeOf(object)


1️⃣ JavaScript Object.defineProperty():
    -> The Object.defineProperty() method can be used to:
        👉 Adding a new property to an object including getters and setters
        👉 Changing property values
        👉 Changing property metadata
        👉 Changing object getters and setters
    
    -> Syntax:
        Object.defineProperty(object, property, descriptor)
    
    -> ✅Adding a new Property:

        const person = {
            firstName: "John",
            lastName: "Doe",
            language: "Nepali",
        };

        //1. add a new property to an object
        Object.defineProperty(person, "country", {
            value: "Nepal"
        });
        document.getElementById("demo1").innerHTML += person.country + "<br>";   // Nepal
        Object.defineProperty(person, "fullName", {
            get: function() {
                return this.firstName + " " + this.lastName;
            }
        });
        document.getElementById("demo1").innerHTML += person.fullName;   // John Doe

    -> ✅Changing a Property Value:

        const person = {
            firstName: "John",
            lastName: "Doe",
            language: "Nepali",
        };

        //2. changing a property value
        Object.defineProperty(person, "lastName", {
            value: "Rai"
        });
        document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML = person.lastName;   // Rai
    
    -> ✅Changing Meta Data:
        👉 All properties have a name. In addition they also have a value. The value is one of the
            property's attributes.
        👉 Other attributes are: enumerable, configurable, and writable.
        👉 These attributes define how the property can be accessed (is it readable?, is it writable?)
        👉 In JavaScript, all attributes can be read, but only the value attribute can be changed
            (and only if the property is writable).
        👉 The following property meta data can be changed:
            writable : true      // Property value can be changed
            enumerable : true    // Property can be enumerated
            configurable : true  // Property can be reconfigured
        
        const person = {
            firstName: "John",
            lastName: "Doe",
            language: "Nepali",
        };

        //3. changing meta data
        Object.defineProperty(person, "firstName", {
            writable: false
        });
        person.firstName = "Bob";
        document.getElementById("demo3").innerHTML = person.firstName;  // John

    -> ✅ Getters and setters can also be changed:
        
        const person = {
            language: "Nepali",
            age: "",
            // defining a getter
            get: function() {
                return this.language;
            },
            // defining a setter
            set: function(age) {
                this.age = age;
            }
        };

        //4. Changing Object getters and setters
            // makes language read-only
        Object.defineProperty(person, "language", {
            writable: false
        });
        person.language = "English";
        document.getElementById("demo4").innerHTML += person.get() + "<br>";    // Nepali

            // makes age read-only
        person.set(30);
        Object.defineProperty(person, "age", {
            writable: false
        });
        person.set(31);
        document.getElementById("demo4").innerHTML += " " + person.age;  // 30


2️⃣ JavaScript getOwnPropertyNames():
    -> The Object.getOwnPropertyNames() method can:
        👉 List object properties

    -> Syntax:
        Object.getOwnPropertyNames(object)

    -> 💡Object.getOwnPropertyNames() will also list properties that is not enumerable:
    -> ✅ List all Object Properties:

        const person = {
            firstName: "John",
            lastName: "Doe",
            country: "Nepal"
        };
    
        document.getElementById("demo1").innerHTML = Object.getOwnPropertyNames(person);  
        // firstName,lastName,country

        Object.defineProperty(person, "firstName", {
            enumerable: false
        });
        document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML += Object.getOwnPropertyNames(person) + "<br>"; 
        // firstName,lastName,country


    -> ⚠️ List Enumerable Object Properties:
        👉 Object.keys() method list enumerable object properties. 
        👉 Syntax:
            Object.keys(object)

            const person = {
                firstName: "John",
                lastName: "Doe",
                country: "Nepal"
            };
            Object.defineProperty(person, "firstName", {
                enumerable: false
            });
            document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML += Object.getOwnPropertyNames(person) + "<br>"; 
            // firstName,lastName,country
            document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML += Object.keys(person);  
            // lastName,country